Exercise 2

get_followers("CSS_GMU") %>%
  pull(user_id) %>%
  lookup_users() %>%
  write_rds(path = path("css_gmu_followers", ext = "rds"))

get_friends("CSS_GMU") %>%
  pull(user_id) %>%
  lookup_users() %>%
  write_rds(path = path("css_gmu_friends", ext = "rds"))

The get_followers() method gets all of the followers of a specified user. lookup_users() pulls the list of users that are associated with that user and puts it into a backend data table, and write_rds puts that data into the offline rds file. Get_friends does the same thign, only with friends instead of followers.

css_gmu_followers <- readRDS("~/finallab-rcpayung/css_gmu_followers.rds")
css_gmu_friends <- readRDS("~/finallab-rcpayung/css_gmu_friends.rds")

Exercise 4

css_gmu_followers %>%
  users_data() %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(
    mapping = aes(x = account_created_at),
    bins = 20
  )

The average age of the accounts that follow css_gmu is roughly normal, with the mode of the accounts creation date at 2009. This means that most of the accounts that follow css_gmu are generally an older crowd (between the ages of 20 and 50), id assume.
